BOC, Wangfujing, Shanghai Construction, Yunnan Salt: China Equity Preview

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-03-24T16:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-24/boc-wangfujing-shanghai-construction-yunnan-salt-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, dropped 0.1 percent to 2,946.71. The
 CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  lost 0.4 percent to 3,251.36.  Rare earth producers: China will raise resource taxes on
rare earth minerals from April 1, China Financial and Economic
News, a publication under the Ministry of Finance, said
yesterday. The tax on mined light rare earths will rise to 60
yuan per ton, the report said.  Inner Mongolia Baotou Steel Rare-Earth Hi-Tech Co. (600111
CH) slid 1.9 percent to 84.05 yuan. Rising Nonferrous Metals
Share Co. (600259 CH) slipped 0.7 percent to 72 yuan.  Bank of China Ltd. (601988)  (601988 CH): The nation’s third-largest
lender by market value said profit rose 29 percent to 104.4
billion yuan ($15.9 billion) last year as economic growth
bolstered demand for financial services and lending
profitability. The stock gained 0.3 percent to 3.29 yuan.  Beijing Wangfujing Department Store (Group) Co. (600859
CH): The company’s 2010 net income fell 2.2 percent from a year
ago to 376 million yuan, according to a statement to the
Shanghai Stock Exchange yesterday. The stock fell 0.9 percent to
41.40 yuan.  Shanghai Construction Co. (600170 CH): The company’s 2010
net income rose 24 percent from a year ago to 916 million yuan,
according to a statement to the  Shanghai Stock Exchange 
yesterday. The stock added 0.2 percent to 16.67 yuan.  Shanghai Mechanical & Electrical Industry Co. (600835 CH):
The company’s 2010 net income rose 43 percent from a year ago to
666 million yuan, according to a statement to the Shanghai Stock
Exchange yesterday. The stock fell 1 percent to 14.34 yuan.  Xiamen Tungsten Co. (600549 CH): The company’s 2010 net
income rose 64 percent from a year ago to 349.9 million yuan,
according to a statement to the Shanghai Stock Exchange
yesterday. The stock gained 0.1 percent to 48.60 yuan.  Yunnan Salt & Chemical Industry Co. (002053 CH): The
company’s 2010 net income fell 7.8 percent from a year ago to
19.5 million yuan, according to a statement to the Shenzhen
Stock Exchange yesterday. The stock rose 0.8 percent to 13.20
yuan.  --Irene Shen. Editors: Glenn Kalinoski,  Brendan Walsh   To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story: Irene Shen at
